Variables are containers to store data 
No need to declare data type (Python figures it out) 

Primitive / Built-in types → int, float, str, bool
Collection types → list, dict, tuple, set

Python's ACTUAL Data Types
Type Example Use int a = 10 
Whole numbers float a = 10.5 
Decimal numbers str a = "hello" 
Text/characters bool a = True True or False 
list a = [1,2,3] Collection of items 
dict a = {"name":"Joshi"} Key-value pairs 
tuple a = (1,2,3) Unchangeable list

  # For integer
age = int(input("Enter age: "))

# For decimal/double → use float NOT double
price = float(input("Enter price: "))

# For text/char → use str (or nothing, default is str)
name = str(input("Enter name: "))

# char doesn't exist — a single character is just a string
letter = input("Enter a letter: ")  # just this is enough

# Variables
a = 10          # int
b = 10.5        # float
c = "Joshi"     # str
d = True        # bool

# Print
print("Hello World")
print(a)

# Input
name = input("Enter name: ")           # text
age = int(input("Enter age: "))        # integer
price = float(input("Enter price: "))  # decimal

# Check data type
print(type(a))   # shows <class 'int'>








  
